„Yes, Captain. You should be on your way by now, they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations.“  Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
„We are being relocated to the forward base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos, to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains,“ explained Shaw. „Depart for your squads and mount up.“
The company dispersed into their respective squads, and the soldiers were assigned by the sergeants to the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat sideways, letting his legs dangle, while he adjusted his backpack and the radio equipment, which was connected to his headphones and a throat microphone.
„Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?“, asked Nemic after they had settled in.
„Do you mean the rooster he stole?“ Cohren remembered the morning they let the animal walk on a farm. „Yes, I think so.“
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he noticed the movement of a small rooster, searching the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
„Yes, he's still with him“, answered Cohren, as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
„All tanks are moving out“, spoke the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the convoy of tanks and Strykers roared to life as they began moving. The Kronos tank Cohren was riding in shook as the brakes were released and they joined the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Due to the winter storms, the swamp areas were frozen and the forests were snow-covered, yet the mud was everywhere.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. „Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?“
„Yes, Operation Firestorm“, answered Cohren. „We thought the matter would be finished in a few weeks, but we underestimated them.“
„Underevaluated is strongly underestimated“, joined Nemic in the conversation. „We were not prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should even have seen them on our way.“
„I stand firmly on the side of the Federation“, said Orson proudly. „I won't let these terrorists scare me.“
„You say that now. But I've seen that most of the eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot“, explained Craith.
„We'll see“, said Cohren laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
„Exodus XO, Exodus CO“, crackled Cohren's radio. „We are detecting heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.“
Cohren climbed up on the tank and put on his special goggles. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could see the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," answered Cohren over his throat mic.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't tell," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, fire only when under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like thermal signatures took shape. As they got closer, one of them ran off hurriedly to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, taking up shooting positions.
„We have enemy contact“, called Shaw over the radio, as orange tracer bullets were fired from the hill. While the tanks were under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket flew by and hit behind the formation in the ground, exploded and scattered debris and rubble on one of the tanks. Another hit sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition flew into the air.
„Iron 1-2 und 1-3, 25 Grad rechts, 300 Meter. Feuer frei“, screamed the commander of the tank column over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, sending mud and rock into the air.
„Send the Sentis in“, called Knoxx, who was observing the hill with a pair of binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, who was wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they set off sprinting. They carried their weapons on their backs.
„Kill or capture?“, asked Craith as they watched.
„It looks like capture“, guessed Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared in the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and gunshots echoed from the hill, but quickly faded away. A short time later, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left traces in the ground. After returning to the safety of the column, they threw the figure to the ground. She moaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure, who was just trying to get up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. „How many?“
„Three dead, Sir“, answered the Sentinel. „The rest fled on foot.“
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. „Get this guy out of my sight!“
